\begin_layout Subsection
Physiological and Affective Computing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Technology is built by and for human individuals.
 However, too often, the interaction between the technology and said individuals
 take the form of psychopathic monologues -- a serie of commands and feedbacks
 disregarding any distress, frustration or pleasure the users express.
 This is because of the inability of machines to understand and express
 human emotions.
 This realization motivated Rosalind Picard to develop the concept of 
\emph on
Affective Computing
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Picard1995"

\end_inset

 along with a whole research agenda.
 Picard defines this concept as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

computing that relates to, arises from, or deliberately influences emotions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Among the many potential technical ways to understand human emotions is
 
\emph on
Physiological Computing
\emph default
.
 Fairclough et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fairclough2009a"

\end_inset

 defines it as a type of computing which uses real-time psychophysiology
 to represent the state of the user -- e.g.
 cognitions, motivation, emotion).
 It then uses this knowledge of the user's internal state to adapt the interacti
ve system in real-time.
 Physiological computing rely on different types of bodily signals, such
 as heart rate, breathing or electrodermal activity that can be detected
 in different ways.
 It is also possible to measure brain activity using varying method; one
 of the most popular one consists in measuring the electrical current at
 the surface of the scalp -- electroencephalography (EEG).
 Measuring brain activity as a communication and control channel for interactive
 systems is a research area on its own: Brain Computer Interfaces (BCI)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wolpaw2000,Wolpaw12"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

