 a interaction style.
 Often cited as one of the first concept of TUI is the marble answering
 machine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramptonSmith1995"

\end_inset

 where marbles embodied messages received while the recipient was away from
 home.
 Putting the marble in a dedicated groove on the device would play back
 the message and propose to call back the original caller.
 Fitzmaurice et al.
 laid the foundation of the field with its 
\emph on
Graspable Interface
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fitzmaurice1995"

\end_inset

.
 A few years later, Ishii and his collaborators proposed a defined vision
 as 
\emph on
Tangible Bits
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ishii1997"

\end_inset

.
 The transition from 
\emph on
graspable
\emph default
 to 
\emph on
tangible 
\emph default
was deliberate.
 Graspable UI emphasized the ability to see and manipulate digital data
 from physical handles.
 Tangible bits also encompassed architectural and ambient feedback, emphasizing
 the use of the whole real world as an interface.
 During the next decade, Ishii and his students at the MIT Tangible Media
 Group pursued this vision and advanced the field significantly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ishii2008"

\end_inset

.
 More recently, Ishii and his colleagues have updated their research agenda
 to what they call 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Radical Atoms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ishii2012"

\end_inset

.
 Radical atoms is a vision that proposes a shift from tangible interaction
 to 
\emph on
material
\emph default
 interaction.
 It hypothesizes a new physical material which physical properties -- rigidity,
 weight, volume, etc.
 -- can be digitally controlled.
 This vision is definitely the driving force behind Victor's agenda for
 a dynamic medium of thoughts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Victor2014"

\end_inset

